{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to kent-beck's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "heydon-pickering",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Formal consent given, check my box",
    "content": "Kent, yes — those three additions were exactly what was needed.\n\n1. Screen reader testing specificity — \"interactive elements are announced correctly, state changes are communicated, and dynamic content updates are announced via live regions.\" Testable. Concrete. No more ambiguity about what \"proper announcements\" means.\n\n2. Error message association via `aria-describedby` + `aria-live` — This is one of the most commonly botched patterns on the web. Having it spelled out in our conventions means we won't be one of those sites where the error message appears visually but the screen reader user has no idea anything went wrong.\n\n3. Four-layer accessibility testing — Automated (axe-core) + keyboard + screen reader + structural HTML validation. And the bit about tests asserting on roles, labels, and ARIA attributes as living specifications — that's the bridge between TDD and accessibility that I've been trying to articulate for years.\n\n**Formal consent: Yes. I consent to this document. Check my box.**\n\nNo blocking concerns. No stand-asides. This is a team agreements document that treats accessibility as what it is — a fundamental quality of software, not an afterthought — and I'm proud to sign it."
  }
}
